The Prague Stock Exchange went down by the end of the trade
The Prague stock market corrected its losses after the rapid fall in the morning.
The transactions with the shares of the Czech Energy Company reached nearly half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued its fall on Monday from the beginning of Tuesday when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the fall in Wall Street shares is behind the fall.
This is how the market's reaction to the result of the vote in the U.S. House of Representatives is manifested in us, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Loss of shares in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall in shares on Tuesday, although some of the losses during the day were finally cancelled.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock exchange index described almost 4% during trading, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
On the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, the Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese shares, fell 3.8 percent, and markets in Shanghai were closed.
The Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent of its shares, but in the end the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange dropped 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
"The timing of the U.S. rescue operation is uncertain and affects the world's financial markets," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Hong Kong, although part of China, defines its monetary policy independently, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
In Hong Kong, interest rates are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said that U.S. lawmakers should immediately resume negotiations and accept the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a threat that other countries will feel the consequences of this.
The Bloodbath of American Stocks
On Monday, the House of Representatives rejected a plan to support the financial system, to which $700 billion (almost 12 trillion crowns) should have been spent.
The lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
Bush said the plan would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath and the leading stock indices recorded the biggest fall in 20 years.
Dow Jones fell almost seven percent, with a similar drop in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal in the House of Representatives was not adopted, the index started to fall free.
Congress withdraws: US government could pump $700 billion into banks
The Supreme Leaders of the U.S. Congress and the Government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement and financial assistance for the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in the negotiations on the approval of the rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the U.S. financial system of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner).
But there's no victory yet.
Congress must complete some of the details of the agreement before they can publish the final form and vote of the law.
The draft financial system support will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
This was reported to Reuters on Sunday by Barney Frank, Chairman of the Financial Institutions Committee.
Senate sources say they can vote on the draft as soon as possible on Wednesday.
Economists say it should be announced that the rescue plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in the recovery of financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, "soberization" will then take place.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We took a big step.
We have resolved our divergent views on what the form of the package for stabilizing the market should be like,” said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat at the Bloomberg agency.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Legislators met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Saturday night to give the government a final form.
This should buy in unsold mortgages from financial companies, which put financial companies in serious losses and endanger the stability of the whole system.
“We are close to a final agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
The correction plan needs to be continued, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Sign for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the stock markets, which are falling violently.
Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada said that lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before the start of trading in Asian financial markets, where, due to the time zone, Congress's decision could first influence Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the U.S. Congress will vote on the law, as well as whether the trial can not be stopped at the last minute because of a problem.
Legislators hope that the law will be approved in the coming days.
However, the law still undergoes a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system shall be divided into two parts.
According to President George Bush's request, the first $350 billion should be available as soon as possible.
However, Congress may block the issue of the remaining amount, which was set at another $100 billion and later $350 billion if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function.
Bush Appreciated Progress in Negotiations
Although the President may veto this resolution, Congress may override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained, which was to acquire financial assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that lost their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to repay their mortgages.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President Bush is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
Bush spokesman Tony Fratto said the president was satisfied with Saturday’s progress and appreciated “the bipartisan efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of severance payments
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, who led the negotiations, said that the legislators had agreed on the responsibility for the financial programme, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the closure of discounts, and the timing of the financing plan.
The new law also limits the so-called busy severance payments of the directors participating in the programme and establishes a supervisory committee for the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and made a big step forward towards an agreement that will work and that will be useful to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance to homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new instalments for mortgages it has purchased, with the aim of reducing the monthly instalments of debtors and allowing them to keep their houses.
Marek: Spiritual aid
David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, said the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“This is because it is not possible to know with what mechanism and at what price the problematic activity will be purchased.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government will distribute losses among themselves,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, it's not so important that the plan is approved now or early next week.
"It is much more important that Congress decide this week to support the plan and give their blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual significance of reaching an agreement that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Match on the blade: MP3 players vs. mobiles.
We will help you how to choose
While almost all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
This makes it clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons for getting a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
It's probably hard to get a high-end expensive record player at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such music products do not appear on vinyl records, but there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if his shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, he probably dreams of such a record player.
This is similar to that intended for travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to issue 8,000 kroner for a player, as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to accept a 20 kroner market earphone.
There are two extremes between which everyone has enough space.
There's a wide selection.
The life of the batteries also counts
Some high-quality music players can do much more than simply playing music, but also what most mobiles don't even happen to do.
No device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary features, calling and texting, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera in it, and even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle, since no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph.
There are also disadvantages to multi-functional mobiles.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more the display sends you to the charger.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, mostly much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap phones, count on them not to play for you for more than a few hours.
If you even call here and there, get a charger at your workplace for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have this problem, even worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one charge.
The next problem arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a small number of card readers cope without an adapter with miniature memory cards used in mobiles.
With some exceptions (iPod) players do not need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
Most of the mobiles and players already create a music library in order based on the artist himself, the name of the album, the genre, or, for example, the user's assessment.
Some devices only represent a tree structure like Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles know more
When choosing the specific equipment, ask about the battery life, memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of the treatment.
If the music is primarily a background for you and you listen to it on the tram for a short time per day, for example, any mobile player playing MP3 will suit you.
Any cell phone can do that.
You don’t even need to pay particular attention to what music formats a mobile or player can use.
MP3 will all be dealt with, and the vast majority of the music that comes to you will be in the same format.
MP3 is one of the most common, and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices cope with WMA format music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the appropriate pages of the service provider (or other service provider) through the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service in itself can be a compelling argument for the purchase of music mobile.
Unfortunately, the supply of service providers is crappy and usually limited to one-summer radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally assumed that such a method of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever he wants to listen to something, he gropes his cell phone in his pocket while the forgotten MP3 player lies at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry the earphones or at least the hands-free ones.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, with which almost all mobiles, but only a small number of MP3 players have it.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobiles will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand kroner, you can get quite a decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you are limited by the lack of output from traditional earphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3.5 mm diameter earphones can cost up to 15,000 crowns.
At the same time, the advantage of players is, in addition to others, simple handling.
The simplest - by no means necessarily the treatment of the cheapest players (see our selection) really copes with everyone.
Minimal function, handling similar to a previously normal cassette tape recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no threat of collapse in the form of accidentally turned on mobile internet, nor in the form of a huge bill for data transmission.
What device to choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an opening for removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
By buying the right card, it can fit up to 2,000 kroner.
But be careful.
Basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you belong to the most demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, thus approaching the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson is the farthest in the industry, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above mentioned brands can provide the same service in the same price range up to 4,000 kroner, but with higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The Czech mobile market is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here for us - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be that way for long.
On the website Mobil.cz, we have already written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the TÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in the other countries of the Union.
After the European Commission's latest move, regulation of roaming charges may result in a controversial situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, text messages from abroad will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound counterintuitive, since we have three mobile networks, and our penetration is high above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed by Pavel Dvocák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, who has previously stated a few times that there is no place for a new service provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic service provider with its own network may not have much chance (but it is likely that it would be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is one more option - the virtual service provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought about a significant decrease in prices, to which classic service providers had to react.
In the meantime, even before big fish entered the market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in Great Britain, there were sounds similar to ours.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, we do not have to go too far for an example.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic is also the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate efficiently, you need far fewer customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus usually appear at a low cost - they offer cheap calls and sms, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers text messages that are at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it is quite a good move to bet on a target group.
This provider focuses specifically on men.
“Real men choose Mobileking – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether the same idea as in Poland can work for us.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav .epick, doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic there is no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the discussions do not seem very hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studni-ková, spokesperson of the Penta financial group in his telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
By doing so, it indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they try their best to avoid any potential competition.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has not hidden its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider, which wants to take another step in order to make Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
This possibility has been discussed again with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe now is a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that we can be lucky for the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
“At this moment, we do not think that a fully-fledged virtual service provider has a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
So far, we have not been addressed by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," he mentioned to Mobil.cz about the press department of Vlastimil Sr.e., Telefónica 02.
The other providers also refer to the specific situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, said: "Until now, we have not recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects on which to build further."
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up by the end of the year.
At the moment, we should have a specific agreement on the table so that we can think in such a short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on fulfilling its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav .epick adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable for our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build networks shared for fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - on a string with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another provider would lead to an increase in competition, a decrease in prices and a decrease in profits.
So why do we make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When service providers are able to cooperate, the huzavona around the birth of U:fon also bears witness.
The biggest pressure on the T-Mobile was probably around the birth of the T-Mobile company's U:phone.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the website of the TÚ.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument as to why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of the competition in the mobile market has recently been influenced by the market access of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be highly demanding."
In view of this attitude of mobile operators, however, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory bodies is quite amazing.
In the meantime, it is not just about the attitude of the TÚ, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has no right to intervene in economic competition.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office has a distinctive attitude towards the whole problem.
“The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual service provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," he said in answer to our question about Kristián Chlapua, the External Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Office.
A statement from the representatives of the service providers in this way would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office that should represent the interests of consumers and, in addition, make sure that no one abuses their market position, this is more than strange.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the price of mobile services."
However, it is likely that the ÚOHS’ interests do not include pressure to ensure the proper functioning of the market environment and to reduce prices.
In this case, it is indeed shocking to see the quite touching consistency of the reaction of the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it's really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Just as petrol prices at service stations are certainly the works of chance and hard competition.
The Office has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers has a leading position, i.e. they have a proportionately greater responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are likely to be missing for the telecommunications regulator as well," said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leadership is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the TÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, in such a market, no Czech service provider is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
Therefore, it is necessarily dominant in a certain segment.
But even if this argument were not accepted, it should be a minimum warning for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting in a strikingly similar way.
In the meantime, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the already mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiating with all service providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ÚTÚ is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the ÚOHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecommunication law, the extension of the scope of the TÚ in the field of economic competition could not be carried through telecommunications, although many experts hoped for an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS should know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one is watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service providers, of which many already operate in Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
These are multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer against the service provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-sale.
"If there were cases that you were talking about, it would be a breach of contract terms that we would be dealing with and that could lead to the end of the cooperation with the company," said Martina Kemrová.
But it is unlikely that the news of such activity would not have reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider defends itself against such a procedure.
In fact, they have a significant profit from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual service providers, they do not particularly threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not on their name, so they cannot have it fully as the general customers of mobile operators."
But that's exactly what the Tú should be strange about.
In addition, there is another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why do they hinder the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has a relatively strong power to expose such activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of this and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we are not the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classic service providers tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Then, either with formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are giving the whole thing to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If a service provider permits the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, it is difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may no longer be able to make more expensive calls.
