Prague transport company will also deliver a chip card for the first time on Wednesday
1 October 2008 Wednesday is the date in the history of the Prague Transport Company when the first passenger enters metros, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon is currently available to about 100,000 people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time save it on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the Transport Company at the metro stations Muzeum, M.stek, Nádra.í Hole.ovice, And.l., Roztyly, Let.any, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Ka.erov and Luka.
From yesterday, coupons can be purchased via the Internet through the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who start using internet trading can permanently forget about the opening windows of metro stations, where they have had to regularly stand long lines for line tickets.
The coupon can be purchased over the Internet and the Opencard card will be saved in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have access to a counter with trained servers who help those interested in shopping online and save their purchased coupons on their cards," said Martin Opatrn, spokesperson for the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic coupons can be saved to Opencard in self-service vending machines equipped in some lobbys.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket managers, and passengers may have already noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budjovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are five of them in the city right now, but there should be eighty by the end of the year," Opatrni added.
The coupon is checked automatically instead of the driver
Managing the vending machines that start working tomorrow is easy.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will be saved on its own.
From tomorrow, electronic coupons will apply not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
So on trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants of the districts of Central Bohemia travel to the capital.
"On the Prague integrated transport trains, the guides were provided with card readers to determine the zone validity of the coupons," explained Filip Drápal from Ropid, which compiled the Prague public transport schedule.
In buses around the city, card readers are installed at the cashier at the driver's office.
Therefore, when boarding, the driver must not only show the chip card, but also place the Opencard at a specified location on the side of the cashier.
This way the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"If, for example, the passenger needs to check the validity of the coupons, the easiest way is to ask the driver for this," Dráp added.
Passengers who do not travel by bus around the city and will not remember when their coupon expires can return to self-service vending machines that save coupons for cards.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the equipment.
The Sudeten wanted a referendum from the United States.
The Sudeten Germans asked to be attached to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from the letter from the collection of the Southern Czech Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the United States of America.
It is said that with this wish some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is also shown in a letter preserved from a private archive, which is now kept in the collection of the Southern Czech Scientific Library.
