Rats have emotions, too.
A rat or a moth escapes in the event of danger. Does this mean that you feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have emotions.
But how can we examine whether they feel the same way when they behave like us?
In the online journal "Edge", famous scientists have been publishing their articles for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in one of its series is looking at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we look at other species and dissect the questions of perception or consciousness in general, we arrive in difficult terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same as many other animals: he pretends to be dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude comparable subjective experiences.
However, I do not believe in this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult for us to transfer our own subjective experiences to those of animals.
On the one hand, human consciousness-related circuits almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and implementation/control functions).
This broad area is more advanced in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other living beings.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as the awareness of who we are, or in the case of design and decision-making ability, it can be reasonably assumed that man is different from even other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
However, even if it were not dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness can be like for other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware it cannot be analysed on the basis of our own experience, then its research will bring us serious problems.
Most of my discussions refer to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more accessible to science.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in the assumption examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be the same or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualisation.
What does this mean for emotions?
This is due to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in the brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defensive system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies a working memory.
In this way, emotions are closely linked to areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially of humans.
In addition to language, perception is divided into fine degrees, because with the help of words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states to describe them to others as well as ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio is of the opinion that emotions come from simpler activities in the cortex and body perception areas of the brain stem, as well as Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it can easily play a role in the emotions surrounding species.
I can't deny it purely theoretically, but I find it unproven.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans in both cases is likely to feel: How can we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in the same way?
A cockroach flees in the event of danger, does he feel fear?
In my opinion, only similar behavior is not yet proof of the same experience.
Although neural comparisons continue to help: rats and humans have similar brainstems, cockroaches don't have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for the emotions?
And even if this could be proved in terms of humans, how can we prove this in the case of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have emotions.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I research the emotional behavior of rats rather than emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is promising at the neural level if the same is measured in rats and humans.
Just as I don't research language and consciousness in rats, I don't research emotions because I don't know if they exist.
This may seem like a short-sighted attitude to someone else, but I'd rather move forward than constantly bump into a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
