For years, scientists have been troubled by a mysterious phenomenon called swing-by anomaly.
Swing-by means the gravitational swing of space probes, in which they gain additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
So the probes can save a large amount of fuel.
The European-American Cassini-Huygens research probe, like the Ulysses solar probe, also used this physical trick.
However, what has amazed researchers for years is that flying objects do not behave fully as expected under the ancient law of gravity.
Instead, there are abnormalities in speed.
The probes are unexpectedly accelerating or slowing down.
Physicists have so far found no explanation for this effect.
The phenomenon was called swing-by anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity may not be entirely correct, which perceives the mass attraction of matter as the curvature of space.
Stephen Adler, an American physicist at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, continues to firmly believe that Einstein was not wrong, and he is trying to explain the swing-by anomaly with the so-called dark matter discovered by astronauts in the universe.
"The anomaly may be caused by dark matter, which may be found all the way to Earth," Adler writes.
The existence of dark matter has only been known to space explorers for ten years.
Obviously, it exerts a gravitational force that can be observed to have an effect on other celestial bodies.
However, matter itself is completely invisible, i.e. it does not emit or reflect any electromagnetic radiation, especially visible light.
Scientists calculate that a good one fifth of the total mass of the universe consists of dark matter.
