A separate city, the pride and ordeal of blacks
In the adventure park in Greater Orlando - a few miles from everything that shines, loud and huge - there is a quiet small town where the pride and complications of the African-American life experience were born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to integrate into the country, and which was Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "The five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, a lot of guajavas and two schools cities without prison."
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival, a series of celebrations in Eatonville in honor of Hurston, the most famous female writer in the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida guidebook published by the Federal Writers Project of the Crisis Age, is separate from its surroundings.
Just as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that urban blacks in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate Barack Obama encourages an open exchange of views on the racial issue, many here are distrustful of the looks of outsiders.
“We’re very careful about how they tell our story,” said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here his whole life and is a member of the oldest church in the city.
"You have to say it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by a paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historical model of black standing, but at the same time a community of almost 2,400 people, where poverty rates reach twice the national average.
Partly a literary node, partly an example of the sometimes despised, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture created as a result of American slavery, which blooms in the shadow of oak trees.
It is not surprising, therefore, that the residents here are both proud and defensive.
The image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (everyone here calls Hurston).
In books written in an honest, strong dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "They Eyes Were Watching God" (1937), he presented his hometown to the world.
Five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook transformed the city, which lies next to Route 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the locations of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, like drum rolling, introduced his readers to Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then looked into the more confidential spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school with a brown background with a white border, carefully kept courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller takes care of, although he can barely read and write."
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything you might need in temporary quarters."
So in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Clearly, Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description did not really please everyone.
"Zora told things the way they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls. Hurston made them immortal by quoting the slippery songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added: “Some people didn’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered here as the living eccentric who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a thundering Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and long pants in a city where people still pride themselves on their dignified clothing.
Most people were fascinated, Franklin said, but a lot of people were foreskin.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair: "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books were no longer published.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with most of the world, had forgotten about it.
Although he was once a popular writer, Langston Hughes' contemporary, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, he was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he used to live.
There were no major commemorations or large public readings in Eatonville.
“I don’t think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston’s biography, published in 2003.
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-track road through the city instead of the two-track main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the community's life.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 motorway connecting the states on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult period of history.
Among other things, forced integration has put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fights about racial mixing tasted hatred with the community.
"At that time, a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at the side of the road," Franklin said.
"There was a woman who died in it.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to force integration, saying of the decision "Brown v. Board of Education" that "it offends rather than respects my species."
Today, residents say that the desegregation of schools was positive in some respects, weakening the cohesion of the Eatonvilles and undermining the self-confidence of young people.
“Black children are used to being hugged, I remember, hugging their teacher in the morning and in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins’ daughter, managing director of the non-profit “Keeping Eatonville Community.”
"This lasted as long as the students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
“We didn’t hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher – I mean there were cultural differences between us,” Nathiri said.
However, human rights have helped many other Zora Neale Hurston rise - black writers, actors, and artists who have overcome prejudice, as she has done, with such optimistic self-confidence and lines as the following: "How can anyone deprive himself of the pleasure of my company!
This is incomprehensible to me.”
In 1975, Alice Walker wandered to Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a respected Hurston biography written by Robert E. Hemenway was placed on the shelves of bookstores, which once again brought him back to America’s role models.
The road construction project would have started just when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again at the center of attention.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
In 1988, the community started organizing a Hurston festival to show what the county would destroy with its main road.
Thousands of fans have arrived at the opening event two years later, and many have returned to the ceremony every January.
Several years later, the county withdrew its proposal for road construction.
"Because of the five lanes on the main road, the community is revived, fully connected, which means real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped to change the image of the city itself.
An increasing number of people outside the city appeared, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who started going to church here in 1993, and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical list in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-storey library (of course named after Hurston) was opened on Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains Florida's cuckoo egg: it's not quite ten kilometers from the center of Orlando, but sometimes you feel like it's a suburban side street during summer rain; it's as small as when 27 black families founded it in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the inhabitants are black.)
They still take care of the outsiders who arrive here looking for Eatonville's story and what he has to say.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things – such as Eatonville’s oldest fresco painted by a white man and depicting black people working in the fields – should not be photographed.
Many people in Eatonville, including the confident Jones teacher, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their separate community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival became more and more widespread, the pride of the hometown grew.
In particular, young people increasingly view Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with his problems and everything, no better, no worse, just as proud, creative, diligent, foolish and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
An honest civic bond is expressed in the words of Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to work for the local government or the police, which he believes need help.
