"I don't take photos on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal point of view." -Günther Bauer
There's no scenery, no ruffles, no dance shoes.
The great masters of flamenco are close by, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday faces of dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, ordinary people.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in intimate moments far away from the audience, when we can watch a personal movement, grasp the depth of a captured look, or we can marvel at the inactive but expressive beauty of the artist's hand, which is not about to perform on stage.
In the German series Günther Bauer Flamenco-people, he combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this less well-known everyday side of masters.
Through the photos, flamenco presents its unique iconography from different angles.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the growing international significance of flamenco every day," the creator believes, adding that Flamenco-people "could be anyone, since when the images were seen, the observer realizes that these images do not typically depict artists.
These people on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
At the same time, stage photography is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the very depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the greats of flamenco with the help of the camera."
The Cante de las Minas festival gave Bauer his long journey in 1997, during which he made portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a record camera.
These portraits evoke classical photography thanks to the camera and the choice of subjects.
However, the use of various stylistic tools breaks with traditional visual representation and suggests modernity. The following idea faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, but it changes day by day and is always fascinating."
It's not the dance, it's not the song or the music in itself, it's the artist's personality and character that fascinates the audience.
In recent days, the leading motif of the works that can be seen in the El Photomata gallery is the search for an encounter with its essence, the artistic crow, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and representation.
Known figures of flamenco, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morene, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are hallmarks of this collection of photos of almost 60 artists.
The project also became a flamenco anthology, about which an album of portraits presented at the exhibition will soon be released.
Bauer's passion for portraits was encouraged to repeat the idea two years ago with the series "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different from this, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portrait.
You meet people, you meet, you meet personalities that you don't even know sometimes, or who only take a few minutes to shoot.
But in spite of these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
The exhibition entitled Flamenco-people, selected from the portraits of contemporary flamenco, can be seen in the El Photomata Gallery, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, at calle de la Mata 20 until 16 October.
