Drunk drivers will be forced to install "Alcolock"
After three drunk driving offences, the Ministry of Interior would require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver was drunk or not blowing into the device.
The proposal was presented in June and is now being dealt with by the State Prosecutor's Office, according to which the pilot project will last for one year.
Since the aim of the project is to restore it to the market, the driver will also have to participate in a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor's Office for Transport Safety, the DG Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Automotive Safety Technology (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of drivers arrested several times for drunk driving are back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air in it. If it is higher than allowed, or if the driver did not blow into the device at all, the system does not allow the car to start.
The cost of the instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the offender.
A study conducted in the USA in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could be saved by this rule every year.
The measure focuses on offences for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from turning into crimes,
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce it, as the legal reform is being implemented in the usual way, while the necessary criminal reform would require a fundamental law amendment.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party that calls for the installation of the system in school buses, as a French model.
