Those who speak in their sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell them what happened to them that day, but those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it's actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure more of you have been told that you spoke last night.
In terms of frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a high fever illness), or more regular (once a day, weekly or monthly), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single cause.
It is often combined with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nighttime alarms, nighttime bedwetting (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As mentioned above, a state with a high fever, or even a stressful situation or an increased excitement can be an accompanying phenomenon.
In any case, it has been studied little so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, it can consist of incoherent words, murmuring, but unlike all this, it can also occur in the form of shouting, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and turn to a specialist. The examination can reveal whether there is a problem that causes great anxiety and thus offer a solution.
As mentioned above, it is a benign phenomenon, and therefore there is no cure for it unless it is accompanied by another manageable form of sleep disorder (e.g. insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things we can do, here are a number of preventive measures:
Make sure your child stays calm before going to bed.
Choose comforting games and avoid making your child watch fear-inducing or more aggressive TV shows or series.
Children who are prone to nervousness or are more difficult to relax are taught some relaxation methods to find inner peace of mind more easily.
This will help the child to sleep more calmly.
If you do start talking while you're asleep, try to keep our calm.
Remember, this is harmless to the child, and the next day they won't remember anything.
Useful advice
Do not wake the child.
It would be unnecessary because the child is unconscious, but he would get out of sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's actually sleeping and resting.
Remember, if you experience severe anxiety more than once, it is advisable to contact a specialist or explore what causes a child to experience a high degree of anxiety.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarest case), do not start asking questions to find out anything about him.
It would be unnecessary, since he is not so conscious as to collect his thoughts during sleep.
On the other hand, you can only hear the speech, but you cannot see the dream images associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you hear and possible conclusions.
Never tell a child that they can question his secrets at night.
Not even a joke.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, since it's just a few minutes of harmless episodes.
