Blood is safe again.
The Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday. President Dr. Francine Décary had a good reason to celebrate, because Hema-Québec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain the trust of people, which was severely shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserve treated by the Canadian Red Cross blood service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and general upheaval, the government of Canada launched an official investigation in February 1994 under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever. The purpose of this was to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to formulate proposals to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed the submission of his report, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood services were established in Canada: one is the Hema-Québec serving Quebec, the other is all the other provinces and the Canadian Blood Supply Society responsible for the care of the two territories.
"When Hema-Québec began its activities in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system," Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
"In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we managed to regain the trust of people." Décary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population considered Hema-Québece reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since the foundation of Hema-Québec on 28 September 1998, the principle of caution has been applied.
During this period, a number of cases of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been managing the company since its foundation in 1998.
“We had no idea if this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we must apply exclusion measures. In this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain changes, inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
And a few years ago, there was no doubt that the disease spread through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of caution."
In 1999, there was a technique on the market that allows the HIV virus to be diagnosed more sensitively. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, not antibodies against the virus on which the tests used earlier were built.
Using the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood using our technical tools, explains the expert.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk of unknowingly infecting blood cells by blood donors and that this could not be detected.
With these improvements, the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions has been greatly reduced.
Today, the risk of receiving HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“In other words, this means we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to be infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions to restore health today, according to Hema-Québec’s No. 1 leader.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogens will be introduced into the system.
After all, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we have to be on guard all the time," Dr. Décary continued, and then stressed that, apart from emergency reserves, Hema-Québec had to provide enough permanent reserves.
“As the population grows older, so do the needs.
Since anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the population of blood donors, since the number of people in the network who can donate blood accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, every healthy person, at least 18 years old, who meets the conditions of fitness, can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have been in a country where malaria destroys are not entitled to donate blood for a year.
“With these 3 percent we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare for us to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones age, because they can no longer donate blood after a while.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In this fast-paced world today, a man hardly has an hour to go to give blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned people.
These tissues are analysed, converted and frozen and placed at Hema-Québec, which also manages Quebec's only public stem cell bank.
Blood can be extracted from the umbilical cord once treated only as medical waste, which is rich in stem cells, thus allowing the treatment of serious diseases (e.g. leukemia).
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the inclusion of the 1,000th cord blood sample in our bank, and we plan to take more than a thousand new samples each year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them for organ transplants," said Dr. Décary, who says that the umbilical cord blood removal program is very popular today.
“Many mothers are sad that they don’t have the opportunity to do so,” he said, “because Hema-Québec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
