The "north plan" is the fourth pillar of the Prime Minister's "vision" of Quebec's future, embodied in a "new economic area", which includes a labour agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and several agreements planned with Ontario.
Recently, the opening to the North (i.e. the northern area starting at 49 degrees latitude) has often been included in the Prime Minister's speeches, but he has never given a lecture on this subject.
However, the head of state merely explained why he considered the North to be “a treasure mine full of huge opportunities”, but he did not talk about the time factor, investment amounts or specific priorities for future projects.
It highlighted only a few opportunities for development: in particular hydroelectric power plants, forestry and, in particular, mining, which is further stimulated by the growth of catching-up countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
In the north there is "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds," Charest said.
This area, which is "twice the size of France", is "our territory, the territory of Quebec.
