Wall Street Rescue: Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the Republican and Democratic leaders of Congress finally reached an agreement yesterday on the economic rescue operation, which has been the largest such plan since the Great Depression in the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months still needs to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
The main points of the plan are: more effective control of implementation by Members; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the envisaged public funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized due to lack of payments; right of access to the salaries of the managers of the companies receiving assistance.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican congressman Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon trial ended.
“We have made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, Bush administration representative.
“We have done everything we can to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“The most important aspect is that if we don’t do that, there will be a huge amount of shock, chaos and confusion in the daily lives of Americans,” said Republican Congressman Judd Gregg.
The trial was accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental effect on the mood of investors.
They gave themselves a deadline for the deal to open the stock market this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed willingness to reach an agreement, but they did not welcome the fact that the situation had increased to the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed himself to the expansion of the agreement with elements such as the provisions on the preservation of house ownership or the payment of the heads of companies assisted by the state.
“When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps because of other people’s irresponsibility, that’s not very welcome.
These steps, however, are necessary," he noted on an American television show.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel if he would vote in favour of the proposed plan, he replied: "I would like to know the details, but I hope I do."
What I have read in broad terms is that it is something that we all have to digest and that we can move on with.
“The opportunity to do nothing is simply unacceptable,” he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers' money would buy the dubious demands of American financial institutions, something at risk, unsold assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the burst of real estate balloons, which first led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgages), then spread to other debt (commercial) securities, and finally caused the freezing of liquid resources and the uproar of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft deal was broken by a group of Republicans last week.
It seems that we have managed to get out of this dead end since the Democrats have agreed that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty will be provided by the government rather than bought up.
In order for all members of Congress to be satisfied, the plan included a provision requiring that if the government had to bear the losses under the programme for five years, it could levy new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion instalment would first be paid, followed by an additional $100 billion if the president considers it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion should be approved by Congress by a new vote.
In exchange for help, Washington acquires a share in the subsidised companies, through which it receives dividends from profits and can sell them after the crisis has ended.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of real estate to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan. In addition, it can set the maximum amount of wages and severance payments that can be paid to the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The drafters of the plan would like the plan to be voted on today by the House of Representatives and Wednesday by the Senate.
However, despite their efforts, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
Yesterday, there were repeated statements against the plan among both Republicans and Democrats.
"It's very clear that Washington can't hear your voice," Scott Garrett, a member of the House's finance committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is nothing that benefits taxpayers.”
Brad Sherman, the Democratic representative who led the small congressional group called the "sceptic faction", presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred outstanding economic experts, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us asking Congress not to hurry and carefully examine which path to take,” Sherman said in a statement.
At the same moment in Europe, it was again understood that this was a global crisis.
Following a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalize part of the Fortis banking group worth EUR 11.2 billion (US$ 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy up its competitor on the verge of bankruptcy after losing EUR 2 million (US$2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis of secondary mortgage loans in the United States.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the 20 largest European banks and ten largest insurance companies.
“This is not wasted money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
“We have the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households appreciate now that the situation promises to be uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Manche, the British government seems to be nationalizing another bank that has been swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all of Bradford and Bringley Bank's ongoing loans, of which real estate loans amount to EUR 41 billion (US$ 75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they would acquire the British bank's subsidiaries and clientele.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock that the British government has wanted to nationalize since the beginning of the crisis.
