The psychology of over-licensing: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
This well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been able to reveal the neurological-economic foundations of neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people do not want to be left behind in a type of competition such as eBay’s auction, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research tried to map the nervous system pattern of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group took part in a player auction, while the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method was used to examine the active brain areas of the experimental persons.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, in which the overlicensing of the other party is an essential element, the subcortical complex striatum was activated intensively when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system, among other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in the price can be explained by avoiding the violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the members of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against a partner in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told how much the real value of the product was, and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they were won out of the game, they would be rewarded with $15 more.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 just before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the members of the group also lost this money.
So the difference between the two groups was that one of them was stressed to win and the other to lose.
However, by proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the "against loss" team were willing to bet higher than the control and "winner" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
To date, they have only explained the phenomena of auctioning with the joy of victory and risk avoidance.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped resolve the contradiction between these two theories by now having a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people with hepatitis at home is 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, the reason for which is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, typical of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (doves, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travelers should be vaccinated against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after eating the infected food, usually accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaint, nausea.
After this, the jaundice on the skin and whites of the eyes develops, the stool becomes bright, the urine becomes dark, the healing can take two to three weeks.
One million people a year worldwide die from the more severe form of the disease, hepatitis B-induced liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the cells of the liver, in many cases only after 20-30 years the first symptoms appear.
Thus, it is very important to carry out early prevention, regular screening tests.
In three groups, there is much more than average: between people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooists.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is currently 200 million in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth contacting the general practitioner when any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
Recognizing the disease in time, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus eliminating infectivity and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by patient organisations around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller that could have made the death of Catholic martyrs easier.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects people's sense of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In the framework of the rather bizarre study, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were given electroshock, while they all studied a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of the pain.
Thanks to the technique that scans the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of research involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university in addition to academics.
The study was conducted precisely by attaching a sparking device to the test subject's left hand, which provided the electroshock.
Researchers asked participants to look closely at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century with Lady Hermeline.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious state among believers, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to be soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts while either looking at the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics reported that during the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" as being "cared for" and "rested, filled with peace".
While looking at the religious image, they reported 12% less pain than when they saw Leonardo’s creation in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself participated in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, including atheists, only the right photo should be found.
“We should find a picture of someone they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should and in many cases will change our personality,” Wright said.
After the great results, the only question is, if Leonardo or a similar-caliber painter showed a picture of a madonna to the believers, how would that affect their pain control?
Would the sight of the Virgin Mary of quality bring even better results?
