The flying of the bumblebee is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collision, if not to mimic obstacle sensors in the natural world?
The bees, for example.
In the surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, bumblebee bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point for building the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C bio-imitation robot control system, a robotized mini-car with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate aim of facilitating the development of a system that eliminates all collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety cover, explained Kazuhhiro Doi, director of technology PR and research and development brand at the exhibition.
The role of the complex eye of the uterus is important, which can see in all directions at an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of a complex eye, engineers touched on the idea of a laser telemeter.
This identifies obstacles in a 180-degree field of vision before BR23C within a 2 metre range, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If that were not the case, the car robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
You need to react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shield, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only towards the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless opportunity for bees to avoid other bees, only rotating movement and acceleration and slowing down were used here as an option available to the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means that they have a longer lifespan than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process data, even less to store it.
This device only has to process and react to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so you constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate bypass technology, which Nissan estimates will be able to enter production cars within ten years.
Another possibility of application is the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to lead the driver to the specified end goal by avoiding obstacles on the road.
