A written version of the $700 billion economic rescue package law to be applied in several instalments to buy bad loans from banks has been completed.
In the first round, half the amount is spent.
According to Eastern Coast time, during further discussions after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders have come to terms with the debate around the $700 billion rescue package that has been going on for days, Reuters reported.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the U.S. House of Representatives, who said the deal is now on paper.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson, speaking of the outcome of the compromise, stated that the programme will work and be effective, but further work is needed. According to Pelosi, this is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the wheel of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets in Washington on Sunday evening 8 (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause a spectacular rise in the fairs.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote on the draft law on the programme, which will be called the 2008 Economic Emergency Stabilization Act, and then the Senate will vote on the law.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night and welcomed the news of the agreement at the White House.
“We are pleased with the progress made last night and appreciate the efforts of the two parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
The program, by the way, differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which would have meant that $700 billion would have been spent on the purchase of low-quality, credit-backed securities.
In the first round, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent immediately after Congress is expected to vote on Monday, of which the Treasury Department will buy credit-backed, low-rated securities, and another $100 billion will depend on the President's decision.
The program will be monitored by a separate body involving the President of the Federal Reserve.
The spending of the other half of the 700 billion depends on a new resolution by Congress.
Under the law, the Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic: you can buy bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities at the same time, as well as other types of "toxic" loans.
The purchase can be made in the framework of auctions and directly, Ministry officials said.
The legislation allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program, where the financial portfolio guarantees the means of concern, for which companies will pay a fee corresponding to the expected damage.
Henry Paulson said that the law provides the necessary tools to get $700 billion to the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the widespread purchase of bad assets, their insurance, or the avoidance of systemic risk associated with the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
However, the bosses of banks in distress and waiting for state help can expect their exit money, which the overseas slang simply calls a gold parachute, to be limited by the government.
Payments are limited only in certain cases, and the limits depend on the way the Ministry of Finance provides assistance.
The restriction essentially means that if the Ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an additional tax will be levied on the gold parachute unless the levitated bank manager is retired.
When buying bad loans directly, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that the management money is not exaggerated.
The image includes the fact that existing gold parachute contracts do not change, the restriction applies only to new ones to encourage participation in the programme.
This is the first time in American history that there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of CEOs, commented the chairman of the House Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank of the Democratic Party.
In addition, the state acquires the right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they can eventually win the transaction as soon as the economy and the bank saved with it recovers.
The bill states that in the next five years, the president will have to submit a proposal to Congress on how to return the expected losses to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed doubts about the plan.
“This is not what American citizens asked us to do, that is, it does not protect taxpayers’ dollars,” Republican Congressman Darrell Issa, California, said in a statement.
Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures were urged by the same people who were responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, the domestic sales prices of the industry increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, KSH reports.
Industrial export sales prices were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 percent higher than in the previous month and 3.2 percent higher than in the previous year.
The domestic sales prices of the industry increased only to a minimum of 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8%), mainly due to a 4.6% monthly price increase in bag and belt production and a 2.5 percent monthly price increase in footwear production.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product production sector (1.6%).
Price reductions occurred in the sectors of oil processing (1.4%), electric machinery, instrument production (0.9%) and, to a minimum, wood processing (0.1%).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, price increases ranged from 0.2% to 0.9%.
In August, prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which represented a significant weight in the domestic sales of industry, increased by 0,3 %, mainly due to the prolonged effect of the official gas price increase carried out from 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, prices increased the most in the petroleum processing sector (32.4%) in terms of domestic sales of the manufacturing sectors.
There was an increase of 13.2 percent in the production of metal processing products sector and 11 percent in the production of food, drink and tobacco.
Price reductions occurred in the textile, textile products (2.5 percent) and electrical machinery and instrument production (0.3 percent) sectors.
Price increases in other manufacturing sectors ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1%.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2% over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 percent a year earlier.
In August, the largest monthly price increase in domestic sales was seen in the capital goods manufacturing sectors (0.7%).
Consumer goods sectors grew by 0.3 percent, and energy and re-use sectors remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase was observed in energy and re-use sectors (16.8%).
We measured a price increase of 6.8% in the consumer goods sectors and a price decrease of 1.4 percent in the capital goods sectors.
In August, the export sales prices of the industry increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to 12 months.
In a month, our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and 7.1% compared to the dollar, and by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and 15.9% compared to the dollar compared to August 2007.
