MP3 players can cause hearing loss
Permanent hearing loss can be caused by longer and high volume listening of portable player devices such as MP3 devices -
In its report published in Brussels, the European Commission, referring to an opinion published today by the EU Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR).
"The report shows that 5-10 percent of people who listen to their portable music players for more than one hour a day for five years can suffer permanent hearing loss," the statement said.
“It is worrying that young people who use high volume portable music players and mobile phones in bulk and frequently are not aware that they can irreversibly damage their hearing,” said Meglena Kuneva.
“Scientific surveys indicate an undisputed risk, and we urgently need to respond,” he added.
The most important task is to inform consumers and disseminate information on this.
In the light of this expertise, we also need to review existing control systems so that they can operate with sufficient efficiency and keep up with the latest technologies."
Brussels has asked the independent scientific committee to investigate the problem in view of the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise pollution they cause.
"Researchers confirm that there is cause for concern, and the European Commission, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, is ready to examine possible measures to protect children and young people from noise pollution caused by portable players and similar devices," said a member of the Committee.
The current European safety regulation defines maximum noise levels that can be emitted by portable music players at 100 dB, but there is increasing concern about hearing loss due to overuse of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions, such as reducing the level and duration of noise damage, which can significantly reduce these hearing losses.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee explains that for those users of portable player devices who listen to music at a high volume (more than 89 decibels) for five hours a week, noise pollution exceeds the current maximum level for noise at work.
If you listen to music in similar conditions for a longer period of time, there is a risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This affects about 5-10% of users of portable devices, which can mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
