The elites are at risk.
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote for the $700 billion rescue package presented by the White House: a significant part of the Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is supported by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis has caused a break in the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided between the traditional, restrained Eastern Coastal attitude supporting federal institutions and business circles and the growing new direction against the Washington and financial world in the central and southern states.
This line was expressed in a critical way during the vote in the House of Representatives mentioned in the introduction.
However, the above event is only one of the significant changes that the still ongoing economic reorganization predicts or allows to be seen, not only in the United States, but throughout the Western world, perhaps even outside it.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the phenomena that have been lurking for a long time, which are solidifying in this new atmosphere and are finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is the re-updating, bringing back to public consciousness the dual category of state sovereignty, in connection with a kind of re-nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis affects banking and financial institutions that, although they have close links with the rest of the world, are, above all, and quite widely, bringing with them people and families living in one country, one state.
This, in turn, is a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
So the crisis seems to be worldwide in an economic sense, but in a political sense it is almost exclusively national.
It seems that political internationalism is essentially out of line: the European Union, which is not able to establish a uniform political direction between different interests and different national strategies, is an eloquent proof of this.
Thus, everyone expects the individual national governments to intervene, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but especially the opening of funds: because only individual states have economic resources, financial resources that may be able to make things right.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that no other market and no international organisation will likely ever have to that extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on nation statehood is fully in line with the fact that economic growth in recent times attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, the increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to dominate the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on things such as water, crops, and oil.
From things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, they are completely linked to a demarcated place, an area.
Thus, whoever dominates the area has much more cards than who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
I would like to move on to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
Anyone who states that territory, state, government, necessarily also says: politics, in other words leadership.
From this point of view, it seems that the economic crisis produces two congruent phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can take control of events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, in particular, brings a total loss of credit to economic leaders, who have proved completely inadequate and have proved that many are still in the dark.
Together, the two are even more important and, in a sense, more disturbing: the feeling of loss of credit, impatience, inadequacy and separation, which affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
It seems, therefore, that a growing population is convinced that the time of the social elite at its peak has expired. It has expired before their actions, experiences, lifestyles, cultures, in the complex sense of the word, have become their own. This makes the social elite increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In a word, the demand for leadership, in a veiled form, feeds a diverse but strong delegation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is manifested in unexpected "humbles" of voters, or in recent times in sudden changes in public mood. For example, the rise of conservatives to power in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of Labour unity in Britain, or the rebellion of American congressional representatives against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right is included).
It seems that the traditional elite, along with its parties, programs, and even its customs, press, and renowned intellectuals, are less and less able to understand, and therefore less and less able to represent what has been happening for some time in the deeper layers of Western society. Furthermore, the economic crisis is growing, spreading and potentially able to create increasingly excessive emotions.
Despite all this, talking about "the imminent rebellion of the masses" would be, frankly, an exaggeration.
