The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones come
An inexhaustible energy source that accounts for 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is only now being discovered by major international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, tides, all renewable energy sources that have been targeted by giants like Chevron, who are now trying to put their hands on it.
They've been researching the possibility of getting energy from the movements of the sea for a hundred years, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research has increased.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of using marine energy was set aside, but today the demand for environmental protection and the re-increase in oil prices give a new impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) estimates in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by facilities that exploit sea waves.
This is twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and signed an agreement on a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
It seemed like a revolutionary step when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies have voted for marine energy, including those who have been committed supporters of traditional energy so far.
“Chevron is studying technologies that harness the energy of the oceans and considering working with us,” a spokesman for an associate company of the American oil giant, the Wall Street Journal, said in a statement.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of a permit issued by the U.S. Energy Commission for the launch of the project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is of no small importance, especially considering that the US is currently producing oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a further drilling plan.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York and Ocean Power in New Jersey are on the way to extract energy from the sea. The amounts invested so far, as far as details can be known, are of increasing interest.
Technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, this is still a rudimentary technology, even because energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
The existing facilities, similar to those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small and therefore do not cause too much problems with the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce energy on a larger scale, it is necessary to have facilities with a significant environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a connected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure turns on a turbine that feeds a generator.
Electricity goes to land on cables under the sea.
For now, there are four similar facilities in the planning phase, which are just waiting for federal approval, some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started powering a shopping mall and parking lot with the help of six submarine turbines located in the East River Strait in New York.
At tides, the movement of water turns the blades of turbines, and this rotating movement feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are just waiting for permissions to use energy.
It's tidal after waves.
At present, special attention should be paid to the opportunities that can be exploited through tidal tides.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, so it can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008 to exploit the energy provided by the tides. This amount is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
